Manuscript Details: Cambridge Cambridge University Library I.i.6.32

A foundation legend of the monastery of Deer (mod. Aberdeenshire) and a set of property records, in Middle Gaelic, added to the Book of Deer, a late first millenium Latin Gospel Book produced under Irish influence somewhere in the north of Britain. The Gaelic texts were almost certainly inscirbed at Deer. They are in Middle Gaelic but with features distinctive to Scottish Gaelic. In addition, there are two short specimens of Old Gaelic within the Gospel Book proper of less certain provenance.

The Book of Deer proper contains at least excerpts of all four Gospels, as well as an office for the visitation of the sick and the Apostles Creed. The Gaelic texts concern the foundation of the monastery of Deer and its property claims.

Main scribe: [unk.] [unk.] (Hand6)References are to manuscript folio and line number (the <pb> and <lb> closed elements).The predominant influence on the language of the Gaelic notes in the Book of Deer is Middle Gaelic. However, it is agreed that the texts contain numerous deviations from the norms of Middle Gaelic as observed in Irish manuscripts. Although sometimes labelled scribal errors (Jackson 1972), they are increasingly recognised as phoneticisms and other dialectal features (Ó Maolalaigh 2008b). This means that the Gaelic Notes are in fact an important source for the history of Scottish Gaelic, especially in the north-east. It is also significant that the five hands and six texts involved share a lot of these dialectal and stylistic features, suggesting that this is is a literary register based on or influenced by a local dialect.Many of the distinctive linguistic features of the notes are to do with pronunciation. Phonetic "mis-spellings" repeatedly correspond with developments later attested in Scottish Gaelic (most fully discussed byÓ Maolalaigh 2008b), such as breaking of vowels, epenthetic vowels, a distinctive system of eclipsis, and the merger of final unstressed -ch and -gh. A few Scottish morphological features are also attested, like the growing predominance of the dative at the expense of the accusative.Another distinctive feature of the Gaelic Notes, as compared to central medieval Irish manuscripts, is the more extensive use of accents, often over consonants as well as over vowels. Again, while it is easy to dismiss this as incompetence, Ó Maolalaigh has shown that it may well constitute a thought-out orthographic system (Ó Maolalaigh 2008a). Further research is needed, to determine whether this is particular to the scribes of the Gaelic Notes or whether it or something like it is employed elsewhere.It should be stressed, however, that the Gaelic Notes also contain numerous distinctively Middle Gaelic features (with roots in Old Gaelic). For example, deuterotonic conjunct verbs are still used, "ro-" still appears as a preverbal particle, and there are instances of adjectival declension.All in all, the Gaelic Notes show the influence of both Middle Gaelic, as known from Irish sources, and local Scottish dialect, bound together by technically adept and innovative literate personnel.Finally, perhaps on account of their high status setting, the Gaelic Notes employ a very restricted range of abbreviations, although the small group that are used are used quite frequently. Lenition dots or ticks, n-strokes, and standard abbreviations of "mac" and "ocus" are the most frequently encountered.ProseNarrativeHagiographyLawScottish scribeScottish manuscriptCreated marked up text and header.

Manuscript Details: London British Library MS. Egerton 2899

'Aingil Dé dom dhín' is a Middle Gaelic verse litany, praising and invoking the protection of seven archangels (one for each of the seven days of the week) and the twelve apostles. It was probably composed in Ireland but inscribed around 1500 on the flyleaf of Egerton 2899,, a Psalter belonging to the Campbells of Glenorchy. It shows little to no influence from Scottish Gaelic but was evidently valued in the elite learned culture of Argyll at the time.

A Middle Gaelic lorica poem; otherwise, the manuscript contains a martyrology with Scottish focus and a Psalter.

Manuscript Details: Edinburgh NLS Adv. MS. 72.2.2

NLS Adv. MS 72.2.2 is mostly a 17th-/18th-century collection of bardic poetry both inscribed and, in many cases, composed by members of the MacMhuirich family. It also includes several leaves from NLS Adv. MS 72.1.34, by Eoghan Mac Phail, which also contain poetry.

Four poems are included in this transcription, 1 and 2 inscribed by Eoghan mac Phail, 3 by Domhnall Mac Mhuirich, and 4 by Niall Mac Mhuirich: (1) 'Goll mear mileat', a panegyric of Goll mac Morna, Finn mac Cumaill's legendary opponent; (2) 'An bfhaca tusa thu fein', a love poem; (3) 'Maith an sgel do sgaoil nar miosg', a praise poem for Ailin, Chief of Clanranald c. 1696; (4) 'Domhnall mac raghnuill rosg mall', an anonymous but potentially near-contemporary panegyric of the eponymous ancestor of Clann Domhnaill. 3 and 4 have been chosen deliberately as examples of late and early bardic poetry respectively.
